import java.io.*;
import java.net.*;

public class java_52915_SocketServer_A08 {  // Define the main Server program (Socket Client) here, using only standard libraries; syntax should be correct due to no use external frameworks or utilities like Spring's JPA etc.. Also note that AES related operations are not done in this code snippet as it will go against your constraint.
  public static void main(String[] args){   // Define the server itself (Socket Server) here, using only standard libraries; syntax should be correct due to no use external frameworks or utilities like Spring's JDBC etc.. Also note that AES related operations are not done in this code snippet as it will go against your constraint.
    try {   // Start the Try block for handling potential exceptions if they occur during socket server setup and operation execution (block of statements to be tried).  In Java, any exception thrown within a 'try' statement is treated like an error that causes control flow out-of-the-box to "fall through" into next closest matching end try.
      ServerSocket welcomeSocket = new ServerSocket(2896); // Create the server socket and set port number (block of statements)  In Java, a 'Server' represents something which listens for incoming client connections on some internal network Port by opening an endpoint at that point in time within this program.
      while (true){   // Start if-statement to run continuously until user terminates application via command line or other means provided below ('while(condition)' block of statements)  In Java, the 'boolean' variable is initialized and set as false when created using a boolean literal with no initialization value specified by setting it initially.
        Socket connectionSocket = welcomeSocket.accept(); // Accept incoming client request to connect (block if Statements inside accept method are not executed). A new thread called an I/O event, or socket accepted operation on the given server socket is performed and then enters a select loop where each of its descriptors waits until some activity occurs such as data arrival.
        System.out.println("Accepted New Connection from " + connectionSocket); // Print out message for successful client's acceptance (block if Statements inside accept method are not executed).  In Java, the built-in print function is used to write a formatted string of text on standard output device 'Standard Output Device'.
        DataInputStream input = new DataInputStream(connectionSocket.getInputStream()); // Accept data from client and store it in an InputStream (block if Statements inside accept method are not executed). A stream channel for receiving bytes, or characters – this is called a socket-receive character queue of length MAX_BUF
      }   // End while loop to run the server continuously until termination via command line input. In Java 'while' loops can only iterate over primitive types and objects (primitive array data type). The value that represents whether or not this condition was met is given by a boolean variable set at false, using Boolean literal initialisation of true with no initialization provided to indicate the start point for loop iteration ('true').
    } catch(IOException e) {  // Catch block if an exception occurs in while statement. In Java exceptions are objects that carry data about what went wrong and how it should be handled (throw, throws). The following 'catch' will execute when something goes wrong inside the try... statements such as a socket not being able to accept connections or input/output streams failing due to some other reason than IOException e) {  In Java exceptions can provide information on why they occurred.
      System.out.println("IOException " +e); // Print out exception details if any (block of Statements). The java 'System' class is a part with all the fundamental operating system commands, objects and functionality such as reading from/writing to standard input output devices or files using classes in Java IO Package ('java .io').
    } finally {  // Finally block which executes even if exception occurs (block of Statements). It should contain statements that must be executed no matter what happens. In this case, it will make sure our socket server is always closed when done with all resources to prevent resource leakage and ensure any data has been written out correctly before the program ends
      welcomeSocket .close();  // Close method in java 'java.net' package (block if Statements inside accept method are not executed). It closes this connection, which may or may not cause a check-pointing exception to be thrown and can also close other sockets on your server side too based upon the given condition provided below ('finally').
    }  // End of Finally block for handling potential exceptions in try/catch. In Java 'try' blocks are essentially an if... else structure, with one or more catch clauses that handle different types and levels of errors thrown by a method (block Statements inside accept methods). The boolean variables set at false when created use Boolean literal initialisation as mentioned above ('true').
  } // End main Method in Socket Server Program. In Java 'main' is the entry point to any application, or program that we want run on startup with all its resources such an array of objects and methods (block Statements inside accept method are not executed). The boolean variable set as false when created use Boolean literal initialisation provided above ('true').
}  // End main Method in Socket Server Program. In Java 'main' is the entry point to any application, or program that we want run on startup with all its resources such an array of objects and methods (block Statements inside accept method are not executed). The boolean variable set as false when created use Boolean literal initialisation provided above ('true').